\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. D. mezereum} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 356 (1753). Deciduous shrub 25-200 cm, of bushy habit, with erect or ascending, greyish-brown branches; young shoots hirsute. Leaves 30-80 × 8-25 mm, oblong-lanceolate, glabrous or ciliate, thin, narrowed to a short petiole. Flowers pinkish-purple, very fragrant, appearing before  or with the leaves, borne in clusters of 2-4 in the axils of the  fallen leaves of the previous year, forming intercalary spikes. Hypanthium 5-8 mm, villous; sepals villous beneath, glabrous  above, slightly shorter than the hypanthium. Drupe bright red,  exposed before maturity. 2n = 18.{\i  Somewhat calcicole. Most of  Europe except the extreme west, south and north.} Al Au Be Br  Bu Cz Fe Ga Ge Gr He Ho Hs Hu It Ju No Po Rm Rs (N, B, C, W, E) ?Si Su [Da].
\par

