\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 7. D. oleoides} Schreber,{\i  Icon. Descr. Pl.} 13 (1766). Evergreen dwarf shrub up to 50 cm (rarely more), with numerous, usually more or less straight branches; young shoots hairy. Leaves 10-45 × 3-12 mm, obovate, oblanceolate, oblong or elliptical, obtuse or acute, coriaceous, usually more or less villous when young, often glabrescent later, at least on upper surface. Flowers white or cream (rarely with hypanthium and lower surface of sepals deep pink), fragrant, subsessile, in terminal, ebracteate heads of 3-6. Hypanthium 6-8 mm, hairy; sepals 5-7 mm, narrowly triangular, acuminate. Drupe red, pubescent, included in hypanthium till ripe. {\i Usually calcicole. Mountains of S. Europe.} Al Bu Co Cr Gr Hs It Ju Sa Si.
\par

